Checks: 7 0

Knit directory: LSR_website_2023/

This reproducible R Markdown analysis was created with workflowr (version 1.6.2). The Checks tab describes the reproducibility checks that were applied when the results were created. The Past versions tab lists the development history.

R Markdown file: up-to-date

Great! Since the R Markdown file has been committed to the Git repository, you know the exact version of the code that produced these results.

Environment: empty

Great job! The global environment was empty. Objects defined in the global environment can affect the analysis in your R Markdown file in unknown ways. For reproduciblity it’s best to always run the code in an empty environment.

Seed: set.seed(20201030)

The command set.seed(20201030) was run prior to running the code in the R Markdown file. Setting a seed ensures that any results that rely on randomness, e.g. subsampling or permutations, are reproducible.

Session information: recorded

Great job! Recording the operating system, R version, and package versions is critical for reproducibility.

Cache: none

Nice! There were no cached chunks for this analysis, so you can be confident that you successfully produced the results during this run.

File paths: relative

Great job! Using relative paths to the files within your workflowr project makes it easier to run your code on other machines.

Repository version: c9c431e

Great! You are using Git for version control. Tracking code development and connecting the code version to the results is critical for reproducibility.

The results in this page were generated with repository version c9c431e. See the Past versions tab to see a history of the changes made to the R Markdown and HTML files.

Note that you need to be careful to ensure that all relevant files for the analysis have been committed to Git prior to generating the results (you can use wflow_publish or wflow_git_commit). workflowr only checks the R Markdown file, but you know if there are other scripts or data files that it depends on. Rmd 69afb05 L-ENA 2020-10-30 license updated

Latest published version: Data extraction methods for systematic review (semi)automation: Update of a living systematic review (version 1; peer review: 3 approved)

This page contains the latest updates to this living review. We have screened and continued the work on this review, a status update and resources are given below.

PRISMA 2020 flow diagram for the review update(s)

This is the PRISMA diagram for the second (submitted not published) review update. It shows the flow of references from base review, as well as updates 1 and 2. The base review included 2 updated searches; the first LSR update included 6 searches; and the current 2024 update included 3 update searches until publication cut-off in August/September 2024.

The PRISMA diagrams were created using a template from Tailored PRISMA 2020 flow diagrams for living systematic reviews: a methodological survey and a proposal and an app to create the PRISMA visualisation is here

LSR update 2 Interactive Maps

These figures represent submitted but not yet published content from the living review.

Data Extraction Architectures

This map shows which kind of AI architecture was used in the included papers to extract the data points of interest. Each paper can include one or more combined architectures.

Data Extraction Granularity

This map shows how granular the data extraction was for each data point of interest.

Data Extraction Scoring and Validation

This map shows which validation metrics were applied in the included papers.

Data Extraction Scope

This map shows from which part of the source texts each included paper extracted the data from.

Data Extraction Source Texts

This map shows from which type of study the included publications extracted data.
